Congress approves transposing of MiFID in force from 1 November
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today by the Congressional vote on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has subjected the public hearing to the regulations that develop the new law, with a view to both coming into force before the end of the year.
Party leaders have consistently highlighted the efforts of MPs and senators to negotiate and agree the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the operators needed for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which is governed by the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will make it possible to provide financial advice services to both specialized firms and to natural or legal persons, and creates a new type of financial services (ESIS) firms, financial consultancy (AFI) that joins in securities, brokering offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the performance of operations with financial instruments is being expanded by adding to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading systems and command internalisation systems to compete with current stock exchange brokers.
Furthermore, the law obliges investment service firms to disseminate information on the market of key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and the ways of coping with risk, and requires a statement of all operations performed to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
During the hearing in the Trade Chamber of Congress, several modifications were included, among which the claim securitised should be considered a "complex" financial instrument, given the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what occurred in the US with high-risk mortgage debts (subprime).
In addition, the trans-conciliation of the directive was used to legally set out the functions that can be held by bachelorists in the field of eco-comedy and corporate management 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977 to set out the professional roles reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as the intermediary to work externally, will not require permission from the CNMV and will be able to provide services for trading in products and customer sourcing for various investment firms at the same time.
The harmonised ISC increased by five-tenths to 4.1% in November
This indicator, which is later used by Eurostat to calculate the European Union inflation index, provides preliminary information on how prices in Spain developed during the month of November.
Its publication corresponds to the policy of Eurostat and the Central European Bank (CEB) to provide data at times and quality comparable to those achieved in the United States.
This preliminary indicator is calculated using the same process as used for the Harmonised Index of Consumer Prices, but using different statistical modeling methods for the estimation of information not yet available at the time of publication.
The Spanish INE (State Institute for Statistics) recalled that the information provided by this provisional indicator is only indicative and therefore does not necessarily coincide with the final figure, which will become known on 14 December of this year.
"The ISC will continue to be maintained at a relatively high level"
Second Deputy Prime Minister and Economy Minister Pedro Solbes said that the November increase of the ISC to 4.1% was a "sign of temporary," but he also predicted that the price index would continue to be at a relatively "high level" in the coming months.
In any case, Solbes clarified to Congress in the congressional halls that "even if it is not a favourable figure," the inflationary differential of Spain vis-à-vis the monetary union has been "more or less" the same in the last two years.
He also explained that November "was less surprising" than the previous month, when the government had not anticipated such a high increase.
"We expected a value of around 4%," the Economy Minister said on the data presented today.
