Fears of a new gas quarrel between Russia and Ukraine
A dispute is currently underway between Russia and Ukraine over the prices of natural gas, and so the risk of Russian supplying to Western Europe of this fuel is increasing.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is driven by a pipeline through Ukraine and any dispute between the two countries is being closely watched.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices for Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two reduced supplies to EU states last year.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge more for Ukraine, as it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its deliveries from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," Ukrainian Economics Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
"Gas in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit charges (to Western Europe) through Ukraine."
The latest major dispute between Moscow and Kiev was caused by a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This has caused an overwhelming fall in exports to Western Europe, raising prices sharply.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but a large proportion of them remain underused.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own deliveries with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
